v.pl/ Presentation The Solidarity Phenomenon] ([[Polish language|PL]], [[English language|EN]], [[German language|DE]], [[French language|FR]], [[Spanish language|ES]], [[Russian language|RU]])\n*[http://commonwealth.pl Commonwealth of Diverse Cultures: Poland's Heritage]\n*[http://psi.ece.jhu.edu/~kaplan/IRUSS/BUK/GBARC/pdfs/poland/poland-rus.html Soviet Archives concerning Poland (1980\u20131984)] by [[Vladimir Bukovsky]]\n*{{Internet Archive short film|id=gov.archives.arc.1703685|name=Poland Reconstruction (1971)}}\n\n{{History of the People's Republic of Poland}}\n{{Years in Poland}}\n{{Poland topics}}\n{{Communist Eastern and Central Europe}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Poland (1945-1989)}}\n[[Category:Contemporary history of Poland|.1945]]\n[[Category:Polish People's Republic|.]]\n[[Category:History of Poland by period|1945]]\n[[Category:1940s in Poland|.]]\n[[Category:1950s in Poland|.]]\n[[Category:1960s in Poland|.]]\n[[Category:1970s in Poland|.]]\n[[Category:1980s in Poland|.]]\n[[Category:Communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Political history of Poland]]\n[[Category:20th century in Poland]]\n", "name_user": "Oliszydlowski", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor rephrasing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Poland_(1945%E2%80%931989)"}
{"title_page": "MSR Studios", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=November 2015}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Technical|date=April 2020}}\n{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''MSR Studios''' was a photography and movie producing company [[Recording studio|recording facility]] in [[New York City]]. MSR Studios was located just outside [[Times Square]] at 168 West 48th street, between 6th and 7th avenues. Originating from the merger of '''Sound on Sound''' and '''Right Track Recording''', the studio was first known as Legacy Studios.\n\n==Studios (Midtown)==\n\n=== Studio A ===\nStudio A was MSR Studios\u2019 largest tracking room and featured a 9\u2032 Yamaha Concert Grand Piano. The control room was outfitted with a 72-input SSL J Series console, a custom Augsperger main monitoring system with custom Leigh Audio Design dual 18\u2033 subwoofers and twenty four Neve 1081 mic pre/eq modules. Four [[Isolation booth|isolation booths]] and a large main recording space made MSR Studio A the perfect choice for any tracking situation. Also available (upon request) was the Endless Analog CLASP system. This allowed for seamless integration of a 24-track analog tape front end to Pro Tools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msrstudiosny.com/portfolio/studio-a/|title=Studio A {{!}} MSR Studios|website=www.msrstudiosny.com|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Studio B ===\nCentered around a [[Euphonix]] System 5 console with EuCon software allowing for DAW control, Studio B was MSR's digital mixing/tracking room. The System 5's ability to handle high track counts within a small footprint made Studio B a great room for film score and Broadway cast album mixes. The 800 square foot live room, which featured a [[Yamaha_Corporation|Yamaha]] C7 piano, could comfortably accommodate any small tracking session.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msrstudiosny.com/portfolio/studio-b/|title=Studio B {{!}} MSR Studios|website=www.msrstudiosny.com|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Studio C ===\nStudio C was MSR Studios\u2019 premier mix room. The studio hosted a 72 input SSL J series console, custom Augsperger mains, Leigh Audio Design dual 18\u2033 subwoofer and a wide array of outboard equipment including eight Neve 1081 mic pre/eq modules. A dedicated machine room allowed for the quiet critical-listening environment necessary for accurate mixing. Studio C also housed a Yamaha C7 piano, convenient for small format tracking including vocals or overdubs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msrstudiosny.com/portfolio/studio-c/|title=Studio C {{!}} MSR Studios|website=www.msrstudiosny.com|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Studio A509  ===\nStudio A509 was an Orchestral Facility. It featured an SSL 9096 - 96 Input with J Series Computer and Full Film Surround Monitor Selectable E and G Series Equalizer in Every Channel 4,600-square-foot (430 m2) live room with 35-foot (11 m) ceiling.\n\nBefore MSR [[Times_Square|Times Square's]] closure, it was sold and torn down.<ref>{{cite web|title=Studio A509|url=http://www.mixonline.com/news/facilities/legacy-studio-a509-close-48th-street-still-strong/367390|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>\n\n== Closure ==\n'''MSR Studios''' ceased operations at its Midtown location in June 2016. Noise levels from the construction of a nearby hotel made recording difficult. It reopened its doors to the public in [[Montclair, New Jersey]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7415544/new-york-city-loses-another-recording-studio-as-msr-plans-to-shutter|title=New York City Loses Another Recording Studio as MSR Plans to Shutter|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.msrstudiosny.com/}}\n\n{{coord|40.75954|-73.98362|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Recording studios in Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=November 2015}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Technical|date=April 2020}}\n{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''MSR Studios''' was a photography and movie producing company [[Recording studio|recording facility]] in [[New York City]]. MSR Studios was located just outside [[Times Square]] at 168 West 48th street, between 6th and 7th avenues. Originating from the merger of '''Sound on Sound''' and '''Right Track Recording''', the studio was first known as Legacy Studios.\n\n==Studios (Midtown)==\nMSR Studios housed 3 [[Recording_studio|studios]].\n\n=== Studio A ===\nStudio A was MSR Studios\u2019 largest tracking room and featured a 9\u2032 Yamaha Concert Grand Piano. The control room was outfitted with a 72-input SSL J Series console, a custom Augsperger main monitoring system with custom Leigh Audio Design dual 18\u2033 subwoofers and twenty four Neve 1081 mic pre/eq modules. Four [[Isolation booth|isolation booths]] and a large main recording space made MSR Studio A the perfect choice for any tracking situation. Also available (upon request) was the Endless Analog CLASP system. This allowed for seamless integration of a 24-track analog tape front end to Pro Tools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msrstudiosny.com/portfolio/studio-a/|title=Studio A {{!}} MSR Studios|website=www.msrstudiosny.com|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Studio B ===\nCentered around a [[Euphonix]] System 5 console with EuCon software allowing for DAW control, Studio B was MSR's digital mixing/tracking room. The System 5's ability to handle high track counts within a small footprint made Studio B a great room for film score and Broadway cast album mixes. The 800 square foot live room, which featured a [[Yamaha_Corporation|Yamaha]] C7 piano, could comfortably accommodate any small tracking session.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msrstudiosny.com/portfolio/studio-b/|title=Studio B {{!}} MSR Studios|website=www.msrstudiosny.com|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Studio C ===\nStudio C was MSR Studios\u2019 premier mix room. The studio hosted a 72 input SSL J series console, custom Augsperger mains, Leigh Audio Design dual 18\u2033 subwoofer and a wide array of outboard equipment including eight Neve 1081 mic pre/eq modules. A dedicated machine room allowed for the quiet critical-listening environment necessary for accurate mixing. Studio C also housed a Yamaha C7 piano, convenient for small format tracking including vocals or overdubs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msrstudiosny.com/portfolio/studio-c/|title=Studio C {{!}} MSR Studios|website=www.msrstudiosny.com|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Studio A509  ===\nStudio A509 was an Orchestral Facility. It featured an SSL 9096 - 96 Input with J Series Computer and Full Film Surround Monitor Selectable E and G Series Equalizer in Every Channel 4,600-square-foot (430 m2) live room with 35-foot (11 m) ceiling.\n\nBefore MSR [[Times_Square|Times Square's]] closure, it was sold and torn down.<ref>{{cite web|title=Studio A509|url=http://www.mixonline.com/news/facilities/legacy-studio-a509-close-48th-street-still-strong/367390|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>\n\n== Closure ==\n'''MSR Studios''' ceased operations at its Midtown location in June 2016. Noise levels from the construction of a nearby hotel made recording difficult. It reopened its doors to the public in [[Montclair, New Jersey]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7415544/new-york-city-loses-another-recording-studio-as-msr-plans-to-shutter|title=New York City Loses Another Recording Studio as MSR Plans to Shutter|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.msrstudiosny.com/}}\n\n{{coord|40.75954|-73.98362|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Recording studios in Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "Jsage5", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStudios (Midtown)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MSR_Studios"}
